How Remoted works:

One process with one thread per configured listener (secure, syslog UDP, syslog TCP).
All listener sockets are bound in the main thread before setuid/chroot so every listener
can bind privileged ports in a single process.

Threading model
-----------------

- Main thread: binds listeners, drops privileges, starts detached listener threads,
  then waits on SIGTERM. On shutdown it closes listener FDs and waits for syslog TCP
  pool work to finish (see Shutdown below).
- One detached thread per <remote> block in ossec.conf (secure, syslog UDP, or syslog TCP).
- Syslog TCP only: each listener runs an accept loop and submits each client connection
  to a bounded thread pool on that listener (not a new process per remote).

Constraints
-----------

- At most one secure <remote> listener per remoted process. Secure mode uses process-global
  keystore state, sendmsg_mutex, and remoted_secure_listener (AR forward and manager threads).
- UDP syslog and secure listeners do not use the syslog TCP worker pool; they handle I/O in
  the listener thread (secure also spawns AR and manager helper threads inside that listener).

Tuning (internal_options.conf)
------------------------------

- ossec.thread_stack_size — stack size (KiB) for worker and listener threads
- remoted.syslog_tcp_worker_pool — syslog TCP pool worker count per TCP listener
- remoted.syslog_tcp_max_tasks — max queued + active syslog TCP tasks per pool (backpressure)

How secured works
-----------------

Three threads in the secure listener:

-Main thread (remote receiver).
  - Receives data from remote clients.
  - If the data is a log, send to analysisd.
  - If data is connection related, send to the manager thread
    (by save_controlmsg).
-AR_Forward (local receiver).
  - Receives data (active responses) locally from analysisd.
  - Forward them to the configured agent.
-Manager (sends data to remote clients).
  - Waits for messages from the main thread (wait_for_msgs).

peer_info and outbound sends are protected by sendmsg_mutex.

How syslog TCP works
--------------------

A bounded thread pool handles each accepted TCP client connection. When the pool is at
capacity, new connections are closed (backpressure).

How syslog UDP works
--------------------

The listener thread receives datagrams and forwards them to analysisd (no worker pool).

Shutdown
--------

On SIGTERM/SIGHUP, remoted closes all listener sockets. Listener threads (detached) exit
when recv/accept fails on the closed FDs; they are not joined.

remoted_wait_for_shutdown() polls syslog TCP thread pools until no active or queued tasks
remain, or until a 60 s timeout. Secure and UDP listener threads are not explicitly joined;
process exit follows pool drain (or timeout). Syslog TCP pools are not destroyed explicitly
at shutdown — acceptable because the process is exiting.
